Introduction

Telomeres are repetitive DNA segments that cap the ends of chromosomes. Telomeres shorten with each cell division and are sensitive to oxidative damage, and short telomeres have been shown to trigger cellular senescence and may be related to lifespan. Telomere length (TL) is therefore considered a promising biomarker of physiological state and of past environmental experiences.

Over the past few years, there has been a lot of interest in using variation in telomere length to understand the drivers of life-history variation in a range of species, including wild birds and mammals. In this practical, we will use data on telomere length in roe deer, collected by Wilbourn and colleagues (2017).

PREPARATION
To familiarise yourself with the topic and study system, read this paper: Wilbourn et al., 2017. Age-dependent associations between telomere length and environmental conditions in roe deer. Biology Letters 13: 20170434. http://dx.doi.org/10.1098/rsbl.2017.0434. A PDF of the paper can also be found on the ELE page.
Furthermore, as Section 2 is largely a repetition from the last two practicals, so if you are short on time I would recommend you focus on Sections 3-5.

Many journals, including Biology Letters, have made it compulsory to make the data on which an article is based publicly available. This is good news for us, as it allows us to reanalyse their data and compare our results to those presented in the paper. The data can be downloaded here or from the ELE page.

Getting started

Importing the data

Copy the data file into a folder on your computer and have a look at it using Excel or the text editor of your choice. Do the column names contain any spaces? Are they short but informative? Do any of the columns contain missing values?

Once you are happy with what your data file looks like, import it into R. You will have to tell R where to find the file using setwd() and then use read.table() to read it into R:

setwd("/This/Is/Path/To/My/Working/Directory")
tl.data <- read.table("rsbl20170434_si_002.csv", header=TRUE, sep = ",", 
                      stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

Note that the file was a comma-seperated (.csv) file, which means that columns are separated by a ,. This is why we specified sep=",". Alternatively, we could also have used read.csv(), which is similar to read.table(), but it expects a .csv. file by default. Also, note that I specified stringsAsFactors = FALSE. This prevents R from converting character variables to factors. Although in this case it wont really matter much, often working with characters is easier than working with factors, especially if we want to manipulate their content (e.g. using substr()).

table(tl.data$Sex, tl.data$Population)

Descriptive statistics

The aggregate() function is a useful tool to obtain some descriptive statistics. For example, to obtain the mean BodyMass per population, we use:

aggregate(tl.data$BodyMass, by=list(tl.data$Population), mean)
  Group.1        x
1      CH 18.60303
2      TF 21.05479

If we would like to use the output from aggregate() for further calculations or to create a plot, we have to store the output. For example, to create an object that contains the mean BodyMass for each age class, we run:

mean.bm.age <- aggregate(tl.data$BodyMass, by=list(tl.data$Age), mean)
mean.bm.age

Unfortunately, the column names of mean.bm.age are not very informative. This can however easily be fixed using the colnames() function:

colnames(mean.bm.age) <- c("Age", "MeanBodyMass")

We can use aggregate() with other functions as well, such as length() or sd(). For example, we can calculate the standard deviation of body mass per age group as follows:

sd.bm.age <- aggregate(tl.data$BodyMass, by=list(tl.data$Age), sd)
colnames(sd.bm.age) <- c("Age", "SdBodyMass")

mean.bm.age$SdBodyMass <- sd.bm.age$SdBodyMass

Missing data

Have another look at the output of summary(). You will see that in this case we are in the fortunate situation that we have no missing data (i.e. our data set contains no NAs). This is not always the case, and this can cause significant problems.

For example, lets create a new BodyMass column in tl.data (called BodyMass2) and at random introduce 5 NAs:

tl.data$BodyMass2 <- tl.data$BodyMass
tl.data$BodyMass2[sample(nrow(tl.data), 5)] <- NA
summary(tl.data$BodyMass2)
   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
   8.70   16.80   20.30   20.07   23.55   29.00       5

EXERCISE 3.2 (HARD)
Above I used the sample() function. Have a look at ?sample and explore how it works. Now use sample() to create a new variable called RandomAge and calculate the mean body mass for each level of RandomAge. Compare these to the mean body mass per age class calculated above. What does this difference suggest with respect to the effect of age on body mass?

If we try to calculate the mean of BodyMass2, we get the following:

mean(tl.data$BodyMass2)
[1] NA

R is very strict when it comes to NAs: As soon as it encounters an NA, it will refuse to calculate a mean. To nevertheless be able to calculate a mean, we will first need to remove any NAs using is.na():

mean(tl.data$BodyMass2[is.na(tl.data$BodyMass2)==FALSE])
[1] 20.0709

Alternatively, we can use na.omit(), which removes all records that contain missing values:

mean(na.omit(tl.data$BodyMass2))
[1] 20.0709

However, be careful when using na.omit(): When applied to a complete data frame (and not a single column as we did above), it will remove all records with NAs, also if the NAs are located in a variable that is not relevant to your analysis.

Finally, mean() very conveniently also has a built-in option to remove NAs:

mean(tl.data$BodyMass2, na.rm = TRUE)
[1] 20.0709

Also,when we try to subset on the basis of variable that contains NAs, R will retain the missing values:

tl.data$BodyMass2[tl.data$BodyMass2 > 26]
 [1]   NA   NA   NA   NA   NA 27.1 28.8 27.1 29.0 26.5 26.5 26.7 27.4 27.0
length(tl.data$BodyMass2[tl.data$BodyMass2 > 26])
[1] 14

This means that if we want the number of individuals that is heavier than 26 kg, we need to explicitly remove any NAs:

tl.data$BodyMass2[is.na(tl.data$BodyMass2)==FALSE & tl.data$BodyMass2 > 26]
[1] 27.1 28.8 27.1 29.0 26.5 26.5 26.7 27.4 27.0
length(tl.data$BodyMass2[is.na(tl.data$BodyMass2)==FALSE & tl.data$BodyMass2 > 26])
[1] 9

Alternatively, we can again use na.omit():

length(tl.data$BodyMass2[na.omit(tl.data$BodyMass2) > 26])
[1] 9

Does telomere length decline with age?

Linear regression

To test if telomeres get shorter with age, we need to do a regression of RTL against Age using lm(), but before we do this, lets look at the distribution of both variables by plotting two histograms:

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
hist(tl.data$Age)
hist(tl.data$RTL)

EXERCISE 3.3
What do you conclude from these histograms? Are they a problem for your linear regression?

To specify our linear model, we first specify the dependent variable (RTL), followed by a ~ and the predictor variable Age:

lm(RTL ~ Age, data = tl.data)

Call:
lm(formula = RTL ~ Age, data = tl.data)

Coefficients:
(Intercept)          Age  
  1.070e+00   -8.134e-05

Although this does provide us with an estimate of the slope and the intercept, it doesnt provide any more information. However, we can use the summary() function (the same one that we use to get more information about our data frame!):

summary(lm(RTL ~ Age, data = tl.data))

Call:
lm(formula = RTL ~ Age, data = tl.data)

Residuals:
     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
-0.36362 -0.12718 -0.00843  0.13783  0.52616 

Coefficients:
              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
(Intercept)  1.070e+00  2.423e-02  44.159   <2e-16 ***
Age         -8.134e-05  4.663e-03  -0.017    0.986    
---
Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Residual standard error: 0.1789 on 137 degrees of freedom
Multiple R-squared:  2.221e-06, Adjusted R-squared:  -0.007297 
F-statistic: 0.0003043 on 1 and 137 DF,  p-value: 0.9861

Instead of using a t-test to test if the slope is significantly different from zero, we could also do an ANOVA:

anova(lm(RTL ~ Age, data = tl.data))
Analysis of Variance Table

Response: RTL
           Df Sum Sq  Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)
Age         1 0.0000 0.000010   3e-04 0.9861
Residuals 137 4.3863 0.032017

EXERCISE 3.4
Compare the output obtained using summary() and anova(). What are the similarities, and what are the differences?

Based on these results, we write in the Results section of our paper something like this: There is little evidence for a relationship between age and relative telomere length (b SE: -8.13 \(\times\) 10-5 4.66 \(\times\) 10-3, \(F_{1,137}\)=0.0003, P = 0.986).

Model diagnostics

To check whether any of the assumptions of linear regression are violated, we first store the output of the model and then use plot() to create four diagnostic plots:

m.rtl.age <- lm(RTL ~ Age, data = tl.data)
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(m.rtl.age)

EXERCISE 3.5
What conclusion do you draw from these diagnostic plots?

The first of the four diagnostic plots shows the residuals of the model plotted against the fitted values. We can extract these values from our model ourself, using resid() and predict():

resid.m.rtl.age <- resid(m.rtl.age)
predict.m.rtl.age <- predict(m.rtl.age)

We can then use these to plot a histogram of the residuals, plot the residuals against the fitted values, and create a quantile-quantile plot of the residuals:

par(mfrow=c(1,3))
hist(resid.m.rtl.age)
plot(resid.m.rtl.age ~ predict.m.rtl.age)
qqnorm(resid.m.rtl.age)
qqline(resid.m.rtl.age)

Plotting a regression

In a final step, we would like to visualise the (apparent lack of a) relationship between telomere length and age using a scatter plot of RTL against Age:

par(mfrow=c(1,1))
plot(RTL ~ Age, data=tl.data)

Although it does the job, we can make this plot look a bit nicer. ?par provides an overview of the many options you have to customise your plot. For example, we can use cex.lab to make our labels a bit larger, col to specify the colour of our symbols, font.lab to create bold axes labels and pch to change the symbols. Furthermore, we can use xlab and ylab to change our axis labels, and xlim and ylim to change the range of our axes.

plot(RTL ~ Age, data=tl.data, cex.lab=1.2, col="grey", font.lab=2, pch=19, 
     xlim=c(0,14), ylim=c(0.5, 1.75), xlab="Age (years)", ylab="Relative telomere length")

Although the relationship is not significant, it would still be nice to include the regression line. We can do this using abline(), which provides a range of options to add straight lines to plots (see ?abline). The easiest way of plotting a regression line is by simply specifying the model within abline():

plot(RTL ~ Age, data=tl.data, cex.lab=1.2, col="grey", font.lab=2, pch=19, 
     xlim=c(0,14), ylim=c(0.5, 1.75), xlab="Age (years)", ylab="Relative telomere length")
abline(m.rtl.age, lty=2, lwd=1.5)

To make it clear that the relationship is not significant, we included lty=2 to plot a dashed rather than a solid line, and we used lwd=1.5 to make it a bit thicker.

Variation in body mass

The effect of age on body mass

Just as we did for RTL, we can test whether BodyMass changes with age by performing a regression:

m.bm.age <- lm(BodyMass ~ Age, data=tl.data)
summary(m.bm.age)

Call:
lm(formula = BodyMass ~ Age, data = tl.data)

Residuals:
   Min     1Q Median     3Q    Max 
-8.755 -2.250 -0.355  2.197  8.950 

Coefficients:
            Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
(Intercept) 16.65656    0.50520  32.971  < 2e-16 ***
Age          0.79847    0.09722   8.213 1.44e-13 ***
---
Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Residual standard error: 3.731 on 137 degrees of freedom
Multiple R-squared:  0.3299,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.325 
F-statistic: 67.45 on 1 and 137 DF,  p-value: 1.439e-13

EXERCISE 3.6
Plot the residuals against the fitted values. What does this suggest?

It is unlikely that individuals continue to grow after a certain age, and hence we would expect a curvilinear effect of age on body mass. We can test this by including age as an additional quadratic term in our model:

m.bm.age.2 <- lm(BodyMass ~ Age + I(Age^2), data=tl.data)
summary(m.bm.age.2)

Call:
lm(formula = BodyMass ~ Age + I(Age^2), data = tl.data)

Residuals:
    Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
-7.4134 -2.1715 -0.1297  1.8307  8.6687 

Coefficients:
            Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
(Intercept) 13.40443    0.61741  21.711  < 2e-16 ***
Age          2.90439    0.29898   9.714  < 2e-16 ***
I(Age^2)    -0.19547    0.02667  -7.329 1.86e-11 ***
---
Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Residual standard error: 3.171 on 136 degrees of freedom
Multiple R-squared:  0.5196,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.5126 
F-statistic: 73.56 on 2 and 136 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

Note that to fit Age^2, we need to write I(Age^2).

We should never rely solely on the output our linear model, but always visualise the relationship as well:

plot(BodyMass ~ Age, data=tl.data, cex.lab=1.2, col="grey", font.lab=2, pch=19, 
     xlab="Age (years)", ylab="Body mass")

This makes it immediately clear that the relationship between Age and BodyMass is not described very well by a straight line.

Unfortunately abline() does not allow us to plot polynomials, but of course we can plot the fitted values instead:

age2.fitted <- predict(m.bm.age.2)
plot(age2.fitted ~ tl.data$Age)

However, what this is has done is create a new plot, rather than add the fitted curve to the scatter plot. To achieve the latter, we use lines() instead of plot():

plot(BodyMass ~ Age, data=tl.data, cex.lab=1.2, col="grey", font.lab=2, pch=19, 
     xlab="Age (years)", ylab="Body mass")
lines(age2.fitted ~ tl.data$Age)

We are getting there, but it has connected the first and the last point. This is a common problem when plotting a line through fitted values: It simply connects one point to the next. It is therefore important to sort the \(x\) variable (in this case Age) and the \(y\) variable (the fitted values for BodyMass) by the \(x\) variable. We can do this using the sort() and order() functions:

plot(BodyMass ~ Age, data=tl.data, cex.lab=1.2, col="grey", font.lab=2, pch=19, 
     xlab="Age (years)", ylab="Body mass")
lines(age2.fitted[order(tl.data$Age)] ~ sort(tl.data$Age))

Instead of fitting Age and Age^2 as continuous variables (i.e. covariates), we can also fit Age as a categorical variable with 13 levels. Although this will result in the estimation of 12 rather than 2 parameters, it does not force the relationship with age to be a 2nd-order polynomial (i.e. a quadratic relationship). On the other hand, while it will tell us whether body mass varies among age classes, it does not tell us how body mass increases and/or decreases with age.

We fit a model similar to m.bm.full, but we fit Age as a factor:

m.bm.age.factor <- lm(BodyMass ~ as.factor(Age), data = tl.data)
summary(m.bm.age.factor)

Call:
lm(formula = BodyMass ~ as.factor(Age), data = tl.data)

Residuals:

Note that in this case all 12 estimates for the effect of of Age are tested against the intercept (Age= 0), which is interesting, but only part of the full story. To obtain the significance of the effect of Age, we therefore need an ANOVA that tests whether there is more variation among age classes than expected by chance:

anova(m.bm.age.factor)
Analysis of Variance Table

Response: BodyMass
                Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value    Pr(>F)    
as.factor(Age)  12 1835.5  152.96  19.073 < 2.2e-16 ***
Residuals      126 1010.5    8.02                      
---
Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Based on this, we report in our paper: There is a significant effect of age on body mass (\(F_{12,126}\)=19.07, P < 0.001).

Differences in body mass between populations

So far we have analysed data for both populations together. However, according to the authors, previous research has shown that both populations experience marked environmental differences. It would therefore be interesting to test if there is a difference in mean BodyMass between both populations. To this end, we again fit a linear model, but this time with Pop as a categorical predictor:

m.bm.pop <- lm(BodyMass ~ Population, data=tl.data)
summary(m.bm.pop)

Simultaneously testing for the effects of age, population and sex

It is not unlikely that body mass does not only differ between populations, but also between males and females, and between the different age classes. To test this, and to estimate the effect of each of these variables on body mass, we can fit a linear model that includes all of these variables as predictors:

m.bm.full <- lm(BodyMass ~ Age + I(Age^2) + Population + Sex, data=tl.data)
summary(m.bm.full)

Call:
lm(formula = BodyMass ~ Age + I(Age^2) + Population + Sex, data = tl.data)

Residuals:
    Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
-6.8140 -1.4168 -0.1849  1.5752  6.7144 

Coefficients:
             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
(Intercept)  10.69917    0.64986  16.464  < 2e-16 ***
Age           3.05265    0.25422  12.008  < 2e-16 ***
I(Age^2)     -0.20146    0.02269  -8.878 3.87e-15 ***
PopulationTF  3.08622    0.45982   6.712 4.96e-10 ***
SexM          1.30071    0.46942   2.771  0.00639 ** 
---

F-statistic: 65.11 on 4 and 134 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

EXERCISE 3.9
Based on this output, what is the predicted body mass of a 5-year old male that lives in the TF population?

Based on their t-value, all of these parameter estimates are significantly different from zero. Although in this case it will give us exactly the same p-values (why?), we can also test the significance of each effect using an ANOVA.

We could use anova():

anova(m.bm.full)
Analysis of Variance Table

Response: BodyMass
            Df Sum Sq Mean Sq  F value    Pr(>F)    
Age          1 938.89  938.89 130.1274 < 2.2e-16 ***
I(Age^2)     1 539.98  539.98  74.8398 1.391e-14 ***
Population   1 344.89  344.89  47.8002 1.747e-10 ***

Although the p-value for the Sex effect is identical to that obtained previously, this is not true for the others. This is because only the Sex effect is estimated while accounting for all the other effects.

This has provided us with the significance of the difference in body mass between both populations, while accounting for all other effects in the model. Note that the p-value is identical to that obtained by the t-test reported by summary().

You now have all the information you need to report the population effect in a publication. For example, you could write something like: After accounting for the effects of age and sex, there was a statistically significant difference in body mass between the two study population, with individuals in the TF population being 3.09 0.46 kg heavier than individuals in the CH population (\(F_{1,134}\)=45.1, P < 0.001).

The effect of age on telomere length, revisited

In section 3, we concluded that there was no evidence for an effect of age on telomere length. However, in section 4 we found strong evidence for differences between both populations in terms of body mass. It might therefore be worth looking at this relationship in both populations separately.

We can start with two separate regressions:

This is looking promising: Although in neither of the two populations the effect is significantly different from zero (although it is close in the TF population), the effects are going in opposite directions.

However, to formally test whether the effect of age differs between the two populations, we need to test whether the interaction between Age and Population is significant:

m.age.pop.int <- lm(RTL ~ Age + Population + Age:Population, data=tl.data)
summary(m.age.pop.int)

m.age.pop.int <- lm(RTL ~ Age*Population, data=tl.data)

EXERCISE 3.13
Does this result match the result reported by the authors?

To conclude, we would like to plot the this result. To do this, we first plot the results for one population, and then use points() to add the results for the other population in a different colour. Finally, we add use legend() to add a legend to the plot:

plot(RTL ~ Age, data=tl.data[tl.data$Pop=="CH",], cex.lab=1.2, xlim=c(0,14), 
     ylim=c(0.5, 1.75), pch=19, col="red", font.lab=2, 
     xlab="Age (years)", ylab="Relative telomere length")

points(RTL ~ Age, data=tl.data[tl.data$Pop=="TF",], pch=19, col="blue")
abline(lm(RTL ~ Age, data=tl.data[tl.data$Pop=="CH",]), col="red", lwd=1.5)
abline(lm(RTL ~ Age, data=tl.data[tl.data$Pop=="TF",]), col="blue", lwd=1.5)

legend(x="topright", legend=c("CH", "TF"), pch=19, lty = 1, 
       col=c("red", "blue"), title="Population", cex=0.8)

TIP
R determines the optimal limits of the axes on the basis of the range of the data used when generating the first plot, and some of the data points added later using points() may fall outside of this range. You can avoid this my determining the range of the complete data set (for example using min() and max()), and use this to set xlim and ylim (as we did above). Alternatively, you could first plot all the data, but use pch=NA (i.e. no symbols), and then add both series of data points.
